# NestJS Backend Conventions

## Module Layout
One feature folder per module:

```
apps/api/src/orders/
  orders.module.ts
  orders.controller.ts
  orders.service.ts
  orders.repository.ts
  dto/
  domain/           # plain types + invariants, framework-free
```

- **Controllers**: thin. Parse input, delegate to the service, shape the response. No business rules.
- **Services**: own the use case. No `@Req` / `@Res`. Return domain types, not Prisma rows.
- **Repositories**: the ONLY place allowed to import `PrismaService`.

## DTOs & Validation
- Every request body/query/param is a DTO class with `class-validator` decorators.
- `ValidationPipe` is global with `{ whitelist: true, forbidNonWhitelisted: true, transform: true }`.
- Never pass raw `req.body` or `any` into a service.

## Errors
- Throw `HttpException` subclasses (`BadRequestException`, `NotFoundException`, `ConflictException`). Never `res.status().json()`.
- Domain errors extend a base `DomainError`; a single exception filter maps them to HTTP.
- Never swallow errors. Log with context, then rethrow or translate.

## Example

```ts
// ❌ BAD — Prisma + business logic in the controller
@Post()
create(@Body() body: any) {
  return this.prisma.order.create({ data: body });
}

// ✅ GOOD
@Post()
create(@Body() dto: CreateOrderDto): Promise<OrderDto> {
  return this.orders.place(dto);
}
```

## Don't
- No cross-feature imports of private providers. If two modules need it, promote it to a shared module.
- No singletons via module-level `const`. Use DI.
- No logging with `console.*`. Use the Nest `Logger`.
